2. CYCLE DETECTION (Undirected Graph)
A cycle exists if we visit an already visited node which is NOT the parent.
Parent = the node from which we came to the current node.
Example:

    0 --- 1
    |     |
    |     |
    2 --- 3

Cycle Exists.
--------------------------------------------------
Idea:
    During DFS:
        If neighbour is already visited
        AND neighbour is NOT the parent
        => Cycle Found
--------------------------------------------------
Code:
visited = set()
def dfs(node, parent):
    visited.add(node)
    for nei in graph[node]:
        if nei not in visited:
            if dfs(nei, node):
                return True
        elif nei != parent:
            return True
    return False
def hasCycle(graph):
    for node in graph:
        if node not in visited:
            if dfs(node, -1):
                return True
    return False
--------------------------------------------------
Why pass parent?
    When we come from node A to node B,
    A is the parent of B.
    B's neighbour list contains A (undirected graph).
    We skip A because it is the parent — not a cycle.
    But if any OTHER already-visited neighbour exists → cycle.
Time Complexity: O(V + E)
