3. SHORTEST PATH (Unweighted Graph)
In an unweighted graph, BFS gives the shortest path.
Why? Because BFS explores level by level — closest nodes first.
Example:
    0 -> 1 -> 3
    0 -> 2 -> 3
    Shortest distance from 0 to 3 = 2
--------------------------------------------------
Why deque instead of list?
    list.pop(0)  → O(n)  (all elements shift left)
    deque.popleft() → O(1)  (no shifting)
   So deque makes BFS efficient.
--------------------------------------------------
Code:
from collections import deque
graph = {
    0: [1, 2],
    1: [0, 3],
    2: [0, 3],
    3: [1, 2, 4],
    4: [3]
}
def shortestPath(graph, start, target):
    q = deque([(start, 0)])   # (node, distance)
    visited = set([start])
    while q:
        node, dist = q.popleft()
        if node == target:
            return dist
        for nei in graph[node]:
            if nei not in visited:
                visited.add(nei)
                q.append((nei, dist + 1))
    return -1
print(shortestPath(graph, 0, 4))

Time Complexity: O(V + E)
