7. DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph)
Definition:
    Directed Graph + No Cycles = DAG
Example:
    DSA
     |
     v
    Graphs
     |
     v
    Advanced Graphs
--------------------------------------------------
Properties:
    - Directed edges (one-way)
    - No cycles (you can never return to the starting node)
    - Used for dependencies and ordering problems
--------------------------------------------------
Applications:
    1. Course Scheduling
       Maths → DSA → Graphs
       Must learn in order.
    2. Build Systems
       Compile A → Compile B → Compile C
    3. Package Dependencies
       Install X before Y before Z
--------------------------------------------------
Topological Sort:
    Linear ordering of nodes such that for every edge u → v,
    node u comes before node v.
    Only possible in a DAG (no cycles).
--------------------------------------------------
Why DAG matters:
    If a cycle exists → topological sort is impossible.
    So "can we complete all courses?" = "does the graph have a cycle?"
